Pantheon Incentive Field Engine (IFE v1.0)

Purpose

Model complex systems by treating:
	•	actors
	•	incentives
	•	constraints
	•	information flows

as a constraint-satisfaction + field dynamics problem.

Goal: find stable system configurations where incentives naturally produce desired outcomes.

⸻

Core Concept

Instead of asking:

“How do we force actors to behave?”

Ask:

“What configuration of incentives makes the desired behavior the easiest path?”

So the system searches for equilibrium states.

⸻

System Representation

Represent a system as a graph:

Actors  → nodes
Incentives → vectors
Constraints → boundaries
Resources → flows
Information → signals

So the environment becomes a decision landscape.

Actors move along gradients of:
	•	reward
	•	cost
	•	risk
	•	status
	•	time delay

⸻

Actor Model

Each actor has an objective function:

maximize: reward – cost – risk
subject to constraints

Typical reward categories:
	1.	money
	2.	time
	3.	status
	4.	security
	5.	autonomy
	6.	reputation
	7.	survival

Weighting differs per actor.

Example:

student:
money 0.4
status 0.2
time 0.1
risk 0.3


⸻

Incentive Vector

Each incentive has:

direction
magnitude
delay
visibility

Example:

student loan incentive
reward: education access
cost: future repayment
delay: 4+ years
visibility: low for teenagers

Delayed + low visibility incentives often create system distortion.

⸻

Constraint Layer

Constraints limit possible states.

Types:

Hard constraints

Cannot be violated.

Examples:
	•	law
	•	physical limits
	•	contracts

Soft constraints

Penalty increases but still possible.

Examples:
	•	social pressure
	•	reputation loss
	•	financial friction

Invisible constraints

Actors don’t perceive them.

Examples:
	•	long-term debt compounding
	•	systemic risk
	•	externalities

These often produce unexpected system behavior.

⸻

Misalignment Detection

System scans for patterns that produce instability.

Pattern 1: Reward–Cost Separation

Actor gets reward but another actor pays cost.

Example:
tuition revenue vs student debt.

⸻

Pattern 2: Time Horizon Mismatch

Short reward + long cost.

Example:
quarterly profit vs long-term company health.

⸻

Pattern 3: Proxy Capture

Metric replaces real goal.

Example:
test scores replacing learning.

⸻

Pattern 4: Lock-In Trap

Actor cannot easily exit system.

Example:
debt obligations or switching costs.

⸻

Pattern 5: Information Asymmetry

One actor has far better knowledge.

Example:
financial institutions vs borrowers.

⸻

Simulation Loop

Basic system solver:

initialize actors
initialize incentives
initialize constraints

repeat
  for actor in system:
      evaluate payoff landscape
      choose best available move
  update system state
  measure equilibrium stability
until convergence

This reveals:
	•	stable equilibria
	•	exploit points
	•	system collapse paths

⸻

Steering Operators

Once misalignment is detected, the engine proposes changes.

Operator 1: Reward Rewrite

Change what produces payoff.

Example:
tie school funding to graduate earnings.

⸻

Operator 2: Cost Reinternalization

Force actor to absorb hidden cost.

Example:
universities share loan default risk.

⸻

Operator 3: Visibility Amplification

Expose hidden outcomes.

Example:
publish degree ROI by program.

⸻

Operator 4: Exit Restoration

Increase ability to leave system.

Example:
loan refinancing or credential portability.

⸻

Operator 5: Delay Adjustment

Align reward timing with consequence timing.

Example:
long-term compensation structures.

⸻

Operator 6: Positive-Sum Reframe

Redesign system so cooperation produces higher payoff than extraction.

Example:
profit-sharing models.

