⸻

Stability Metrics

System health is evaluated using:

alignment index
externality load
lock-in severity
information asymmetry
time horizon mismatch
resilience to gaming

Low scores indicate system drift toward exploitation.

⸻

Example: Student Loan System

Actors:
	•	students
	•	universities
	•	lenders
	•	government
	•	employers

Detected patterns:

reward-cost separation
time horizon mismatch
information asymmetry
lock-in trap

Possible steering actions:
	•	cap borrowing by program earnings
	•	risk-sharing with universities
	•	transparent ROI data
	•	expanded apprenticeship pathways
	•	refinance options

⸻

Emergent Property

When incentives align properly, the system becomes self-correcting.

Actors pursue their own interest, but the result benefits the system.

This is the core of good institutional design.

⸻

Pantheon Translation

Think of incentives as terrain slopes.

Actors move downhill toward reward.

System design = shaping the terrain.

A well-designed terrain makes:
	•	harmful behavior uphill
	•	beneficial behavior downhill

